<h1 class="hero-h">AI Rollout Mistakes by Company Size <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">The mistakes shift by stage.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">Generic "AI rollout best practices" miss that the failure modes change dramatically by company size. A 15-person company fails differently than a 150-person one. Here's the size-specific guide.</p>
<div class="tldr"><div class="tldr-l">Short answer</div><p class="tldr-p">At <20 people: too much DIY, no documented learnings. At 20-50: too many tools, no named owner. At 50-150: committee paralysis, plans that never ship. At 150-500: enterprise paralysis, IT bottlenecks, vendor-driven instead of business-driven. Diagnose by size; fix specifically.</p></div>
</div></div>

<div style="background:#0A1A0A;border-top:1px solid #1A3A1A;border-bottom:1px solid #1A3A1A;padding:1.25rem 2.5rem;">
<div style="max-width:880px;margin:0 auto;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;gap:1rem;flex-wrap:wrap;font-size:0.78rem;color:#8FAF8F;">
<div>By <a href="/about" style="color:#F0FFF0;text-decoration:none;font-weight:500;">Bill Colbert</a> · <span style="color:#4A6A4A;">Founder, Treetop Growth Strategy</span></div>
<div style="color:#4A6A4A;">Published May 2026 · <a href="/content-library" style="color:#8FAF8F;text-decoration:none;">More from the library</a></div>
</div>
</div>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">Under 20 people — the startup trap</h2><h3 class="h3">Common mistakes</h3><ul class="ul"><li>Founder is the only AI user; team never gets fluent.</li><li>All learning lives in one person's head; nothing gets documented.</li><li>Tools get adopted, used briefly, abandoned, repeated.</li><li>Founder picks tools by reading TechCrunch; not by business need.</li><li>AI usage is shadow; no policy; eventual surprise when a customer asks.</li></ul><h3 class="h3">What works</h3><ul class="ul"><li>Founder uses AI heavily AND brings 2-3 team members along.</li><li>One shared prompt library — even if just a Google Doc.</li><li>A 30-min weekly demo where someone shows what they've learned.</li><li>Pick one tool; resist the new-shiny urge for 90 days.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">20-50 people — the mid-market trap</h2><h3 class="h3">Common mistakes</h3><ul class="ul"><li>Buying 6-10 specialized AI tools that all duplicate Claude/ChatGPT.</li><li>No named AI lead; "everyone is responsible."</li><li>Workflows planned in meetings but never shipped.</li><li>Different teams using different tools; no policy.</li><li>Hiring a "Head of AI" before there's enough AI work to head.</li></ul><h3 class="h3">What works</h3><ul class="ul"><li>One LLM platform + your existing CRM + transcription tool. Resist the rest.</li><li>Name one AI lead with 8-12 hrs/week protected.</li><li>Ship one workflow in 30 days. Then the next. Sequential.</li><li>Publish a one-page AI policy by month 2.</li><li>External help for the first implementation if internal resources are stretched.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">50-150 people — the growth-stage trap</h2><h3 class="h3">Common mistakes</h3><ul class="ul"><li>AI committee with 6-8 people; nothing decided.</li><li>"AI strategy" engagements that produce decks but no shipped work.</li><li>Trying to roll out across all functions in parallel.</li><li>Hiring a Head of AI without shipped AI work first.</li><li>Underestimating change management.</li></ul><h3 class="h3">What works</h3><ul class="ul"><li>Replace the committee with one decisive AI lead (often the COO or Chief of Staff).</li><li>Roadmap, not strategy.</li><li>Sequential rollout: one function per quarter.</li><li>Hire a Head of AI only after you've shipped 5-10 workflows successfully.</li><li>Treat change management as 50% of the work.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">150-500 people — the enterprise-creep trap</h2><h3 class="h3">Common mistakes</h3><ul class="ul"><li>IT/security review takes 6 months for what should take 4 weeks.</li><li>Vendor-driven roadmaps — buying what vendors pitch instead of building what business needs.</li><li>AI "Center of Excellence" that becomes a bureaucracy.</li><li>Pilot purgatory — many pilots, few productionized.</li><li>Federated rollouts with no shared standards.</li></ul><h3 class="h3">What works</h3><ul class="ul"><li>Fast-track IT review for enterprise-tier tools you've vetted at executive level.</li><li>Business-driven roadmaps. Vendors serve the plan, not the reverse.</li><li>Small federation team — not an AI CoE. Standards, not gatekeeping.</li><li>Bias toward production. Kill pilots that don't have a defined ship date.</li><li>Cross-functional AI guild that shares prompts and patterns. Voluntary.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">500+ people — beyond our advice</h2><p class="body">At 500+, the playbook is genuinely different. Different governance, different tooling, different risk profile, different vendor relationships. We are not the right advisors for this segment; engagements at this scale should go to firms specialized in enterprise rollout.</p></div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">FAQ</h2>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Where do most rollouts get stuck?</h3><p class="faq-qa">50-150 person range. Too big for founder-led, too small for enterprise structure. Committee paralysis is the most common failure mode.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Should I model my rollout on a bigger company's?</h3><p class="faq-qa">No. Failure modes scale with size. Borrowing a 500-person playbook at 50 people produces paralysis.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">What if I'm growing fast and span multiple stages?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Plan for the stage you'll be in 12 months from now, not today.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Should we hire a Head of AI?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Almost never at <100 people. Usually right at 250+. The window in between is judgment-call.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Can outside help fix the wrong-stage problem?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Yes — sometimes the most valuable thing a consultant does is steer you away from over- or under-scoped rollouts.</p></div>
</div></section>

